Running RNA.seq datasets requires a large amount of memory. Therefore, I created and worked through a Google Cloud console virtual machine (VM).
Only four datasets were used for this work. 
Two of them correspond to ASD samples, and two correspond to "Normal"/ control samples. 

  # Steps to create your own VM using Google Cloud.
1. Go to cloud.google.com
at the top right corner, click on "console"
2. At the top left corner, click on the options tab
It'll display several options; look for "Compute engine"
3. Click on VM instances
4. Create an instance.
5. Add a machine configuration name.
6. Choose a machine option. I chose C3D: Consistently high performance
7. In machine type, I chose: e2-highmem-2(2vCPU,1core,16GBmemory)
8. IN OS and storage: change the size GB from 10 to 100
9. Create, and it is ready to use

If you are new to Google Cloud, currently (June 8 2026) 
Google has a promotion; they'll give you $300 in free credit. I used this credit to run the RNA-seq data. 
However, every time you use the VM, you'll be charged either from the available credit or from your credit card.
